The learning curve for non-markup-expert authors to start writing and editing structured documents in XML is steep, and there are some specific barriers to the acceptance of editor interfaces (
). In exploring the reasons behind these barriers, we identified some changes that could be made to common interfaces to improve acceptability (
).

This is a necessary requirement in many fields where the content is complex: for example encoding literary or historical documents in TEI, or writing computer systems documentation in DocBook. The author needs to understand what markup is available so that it can be used to describe the finely-detailed features accurately, but the naming and function of the markup is not always entirely obvious (
